<br>
What is really going on here is that ppl are singling Wal-Mart out b/c it is in so many locations.  You are saying that just b/c Wal-Mart is the only &quot;good&quot; place to work in a certain area that it take up the burden of supplying all employees with the same level of care.  What would those same ppl do if there wasn't a Wal-Mart to work part-time at?  They'd be 10x worse off or they'd have to move to find a job.  I come from a town where is is no Wal-Mart.  There is a Dairy Queen, a Minit Mart, Sav-a-Lot and a Dollar Store.  All of which employ roughly 10 employees each, managers included.  Do you really think that those 40 ppl are being paid so much better b/c there is no Wal-Mart?  If anything I'd say they're probably starting out at less.  Atleast Wal-Mart is paying above minimum, you seem to be missing that fact.  And they don't promise to hire everyone full-time, so why should they have to?  It is not an employers responsibility to ensure that part-time employees can survive on that income alone.  There is no way anyone can survive on part-time employment, and if they're trying to do so then it is their own fault.  I specifically dont want to hear that there is just &quot;nothing esle to do.&quot;  Anyone can move to find better work, americans have been doing it for decades, and if you come out of high school and have absolutely no prospects then there are 4 branches of the military who would be happy to train you and pay you.  <br>
<br>
Wal-Mart can't be blamed for the cycle of poverty.  Anyone can find a way to better themselves, and most anyone who tries to find a way, does.  But the problem is all these ppl your heart is bleeding for are probably saying, &quot;I dont want to move, I dont want to work in a factory, I dont want to work 2 jobs...Why oh why won't Wal-Mart let me go full time?&quot;  <br>
<br>
So go cry me a damn river about people who want to stay in a part-time job and expect to get by based solely on that income.  The bottom line is that Wal-Mart payes better than a lot of places, they just don't let everyone go full-time so they don't have to provide everyone with benefits, what do you think would happen if they fired all the part-time and hired only full-time w/ benefits.  The work force would shrink from over 100 per store maybe 40 people.  How much better of would the community be then?  I bet those 40 would be thrilled to make 20k a year + benefits, but what about all the part-timers who went from 12k to nothing so others could have better jobs? <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><br>
