<br>
The Living Wage &quot;idea&quot; is something of a <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.livingwagecampaign.org/" target="top">movement</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, backed by organized labor, to increase the level of wages for employees.  It is completely different than the minimum wage law.<br>
<br>
Hope that helps... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sighkoxblumpkin>Sighkox Blumpkin</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ihateaol.co.uk/misc/galleries/show.php/thumbnail//funnypics/thread_direction.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 175<br> <font color=#333333>(11/6/03 3:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2316.topic&index=45>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: pashaaa...</span><hr size=1> Boston implemented a living wage.  Here's just one story to show what it does:<br>
<br>
A small day care center had to start paying its caretakers more.  They couldn't afford to do that, since raising rates is out of the question since most of the customers make the &quot;living wage&quot; as well.  They lay off a bunch of workers due to this shortfall in money.  Lots of kids are left without day care and the mothers can't afford to pay the new rates charged by the day care centers, so they have to quit their jobs or do some other drastic measures.  IT DOESN'T work.<br>
<br>
Would you buy a TV at Wal Mart for $200, or would you pay $300 at some store who has better benefits for their employees?  Good for you if you can afford to stand by your principles, but most of us can't.<br>
<br>
Face it, two dimensional thinking is basically all this &quot;living wage&quot; crap is.  SOMEONE has to pay in the end.<br>
